annotation.TEXT: A reference to the venerable self-help book Men Who Hate Women & the Women Who Love Them by Susan Forward and Joan Torres.
A line from “The Unicorn,” a song written by poet Shel Silverstein that became a hit for The Irish Rovers in 1968.
Playwright Abe Burrows wrote Guys and Dolls and How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying, among many others.
Burberry is a British high-end fashion house founded in 1856, most famous for its iconic trench coat.
Operation is a classic board game where players use tweezers to remove “organs” from the “patient.” Brush the sensors on the side of the cavity and a buzzer sounds.
In 1963 Dallas strip club owner Jack Ruby shot and killed Lee Harvey Oswald, the accused assassin of President John F. Kennedy.
Mike Nelson apparently said in an interview that this voice is a combination of Bob Newhart and Inspector Clouseau, leaning more toward Clouseau.
Pottersville is the name of Bedford Falls during the “what if” segment in It’s a Wonderful Life—it’s full of sleazy nightclubs, strippers, and pawn shops.
The Sawzall is a brand name for a reciprocating saw, or an electric saw that cuts in a back-and-forth motion.
Clutch Cargo was a TV show that superimposed the voice actors’ lips on the animated characters, with truly bizarre results.
Helen and Stanley Roper were the suspicious landlords on Three’s Company. In 1979 they got a spinoff, but it only lasted one season.
An imitation of Bob Newhart, who played an edgy driving instructor in one of his classic standup routines.
An imitation of John Merrick in the 1980 David Lynch film The Elephant Man.
This would seem to be the 5th Dimension song “Up, Up and Away,” except Crow didn’t get the words right and can’t carry a tune, so we can’t be certain.
An imitation of Harry Caray, longtime announcer for the Chicago White Sox and then the Chicago Cubs.
Mel Blanc was a renowned Warner Bros. voiceover artist. His characters included Bugs Bunny, Daffy Duck, Porky Pig, Pepé Le Pew, and more.
Voluptuous brunette Jane Russell was one of Hollywood’s leading ladies in the ‘40s and ‘50s. She starred opposite Marilyn Monroe in Gentlemen Prefer Blondes.
H.P. Lovecraft wrote a short story called “Herbert West—Reanimator.” In 1985 it was turned into a horror comedy film called Re-Animator.
An imitation of the opening of “Point of Law,” a legal segment hosted by Charlie Boone that aired for more than 50 years on Minneapolis radio station WCCO.
Hai Karate was a cheap aftershave in the ‘70s. It included self-defense instructions with every bottle to help men fight off the women who would flock to them.
Six Characters in Search of an Author is a play by Luigi Pirandello in which six fictional characters interrupt a play rehearsal and beg the director to help them finish their story.
An imitation of ‘70s game show mainstay Charles Nelson Reilly.
The house in the sitcom Father Knows Best was first used in the “Blondie” serials; later it was the Wilson house in Dennis the Menace and Major Nelson’s home in I Dream of Jeannie.
Adolf Hitler, along with his silly toothbrush mustache, was the dictator of Germany during WWII.
An imitation of comedian Jackie Gleason on The Jackie Gleason Show. The actors listed appeared in Honeymooners sketches.
From the song of the same name, recorded by Tommy Dorsey in 1935.
Larry Storch is best known for the TV series F Troop and as a voiceover artist in dozens of cartoons.
Faye Dunaway is a revered actress who made it big in the ‘70s in such films as Chinatown and Network.
The original Arsenio Hall Show was a late-night talk show that aired from 1989-94. A second series aired in 2013-14.
Cradle cap is a skin problem common among young babies in which a crusty, scaly rash forms on the scalp.
Singer/actress Cher has been the subject of outlandish rumors about the plastic surgery she has had done, thanks to her seemingly eternal youth. (She denies them.)
A reference to Episode 520, Radar Secret Service.
Señor Wences was a Spanish ventriloquist who made frequent appearances on The Ed Sullivan Show. He died in 1999 at the age of 103.
Sylvia Plath was a poet and novelist whose works generally dealt with themes of alienation and death. She killed herself in 1963.
A reference to any number of Star Trek episodes.
In 1991 Danny Bonaduce (The Partridge Family) was arrested for assaulting a transvestite prostitute whom he had mistaken for a woman.
Science Diet is a brand of pet food created in the ‘60s by a vet for a seeing-eye dog with kidney disease.
Be sure to let us know if we missed any references!
The Nobel Prize is actually six prizes, established by Swedish industrialist Alfred Nobel and awarded annually for significant achievements in various fields.
A paraphrase of the song “You Don’t Bring Me Flowers,” which was a monster hit for Neil Diamond and Barbra Streisand in 1978.
Did we miss any references? Let us know in the comments!
A reference to Episode 320, The Unearthly.
Music Through the Night is a late-night classical music program broadcast on many NPR affiliate radio stations.
Dylan Thomas was a Welsh poet; he was known for heavy drinking binges, but pneumonia got him in the end.
“You’re soaking in it” was the slogan in a long-running series of ads for Palmolive dish soap, featuring Madge the manicurist.
A paraphrase of the Rick James song “Super Freak.”
James Finlayson was a bald, mustachioed comedian known for his double take followed by a slow burn, seen most famously in a series of Laurel & Hardy shorts.
Carol Merrill was the model on the TV game show Let’s Make a Deal from 1963-1977.
Rocky Graziano became the world middleweight boxing champion in 1947.
Edmund Kean was a renowned English Shakespearean actor in the early 19th century. He collapsed during a performance of Othello and died a few weeks later.
Comedian Ruth Buzzi was a regular on Rowan & Martin’s Laugh-In, a ‘60s sketch comedy series.
A reference to the Janet Jackson song “Rhythm Nation” from the album of the same name.
John C. Holmes and Harry Reems were both well-known male porn stars during the 1970s.
Escanaba is a city on the upper peninsula of Michigan, population about 13,000.
Sister Bertrille was the “flying nun” in the TV series of the same name. The phrase is a parody of the terrible TV movie They Saved Hitler’s Brain.
A tagline from Burger King TV ads that aired in the early ‘90s; they featured MTV “personality” Dan Cortese.
Master Lock is a Milwaukee-based manufacturer of padlocks and other security products.
In 1993, hundreds of people got sick (and several kids died) from E. coli in burger meat from Jack in the Box restaurants.
Eggo frozen waffles were originally called “Froffles,” a combination of “frozen” and “waffles,” but the name was changed after two years to reflect the product’s eggy taste.
In the Manson Family murders committed in LA in 1969, one of the killers wrote the word “pig” on the front door of actress Sharon Tate’s house in her blood.
Salisbury steak was invented in the late 19th century by Dr. J.H. Salisbury as part of a low-carb diet.
On Soupy Sales, White Fang was “the biggest and meanest dog in the USA.” You only ever saw his huge paw coming in from one side of the screen.
With annotations provided by The Annotated MST website.
A skillet scrambler is a popular breakfast dish at restaurants: eggs scrambled with a variety of ingredients, such as cheese, potatoes, sausage, etc.
A line from the song “Leader of the Pack” by The Shangri-Las.
“With this ring, I thee wed” is from the Anglican marriage ceremony in the Book of Common Prayer, first published in 1549.
On the ‘80s TV talent show Star Search, hosted by Ed McMahon, one of the categories contestants could compete in for a $100K prize was “Spokesmodel.”
A riff on “Jet Song” from the Broadway musical (and subsequent movie) West Side Story.
Casey Kasem was the longtime host of the radio show American Top 40, which regularly featured “long distance dedications” from listeners to loved ones.
An imitation of Gale Gordon, who played Lucille Ball’s boss, Theodore J. Mooney, on The Lucy Show.
This well-known phrase is spoken by the announcer on the long-running TV game show The Price Is Right.
Putting a sleeping person’s hand in a bowl of warm water supposedly makes them wet the bed.
I'll Take Sweden is a comedy film starring Bob Hope as a man who takes his daughter to Sweden to get her away from an unsuitable suitor.
The Brain That Wouldn't Die: Fully annotated by The Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Brawny is a brand of paper towels with a hunky lumberjack mascot on the wrapper.
Lucie Arnaz is the daughter of Lucille Ball and Desi Arnaz. She got her own short-lived TV show in 1985.
The term “ancient astronauts” comes from Chariots of the Gods?, a book arguing that ancient artifacts like Stonehenge were built with the help of aliens.
Chicken McNuggets are fried chicken bits served at McDonald’s fast food restaurants. They come in four shapes: bell, ball, bowtie, and boot.
What’s My Line? was a TV game show in which a panel of celebrities would try to guess the jobs of contestants with unusual occupations.
We hope you enjoyed the fully-annotated Brain That Wouldn't Die
Perpetual drunk Crazy Guggenheim, played by Frank Fontaine, was a character on The Jackie Gleason Show.
Gnip Gnop, or “ping pong” spelled backwards, was a table-top game released during the ‘70s.
An urban legend from the ‘60s had a babysitter taunted by phone calls from a madman that, when traced, turned out to be from within the home.
Actress Delta Burke is best known for the TV show Designing Women. She famously feuded with co-star Dixie Carter and the show’s creators and was eventually let go.
Charlie Chaplin’s “tramp” character had no name, but Chaplin always referred to him as “the little fellow.”
“Mrs. Olson” was a pitchwoman for Folger’s coffee in ads during the ‘60s and ‘70s. She was played by Virginia Christine.
Carrot Top (real name Scott Thompson) is a red-headed prop comic.
In WWII propaganda films, Japanese soldiers sometimes screamed “You die, Joe!” as they attacked the courageous GIs.
An imitation of game show announcers, particularly on The Price Is Right, when the stage doors would part and reveal “A new car!”
The music video for the Peter Gabriel song “Sledgehammer” is a closeup on Gabriel's face singing the song while stop-motion shenanigans go on around him.
In 1992 Shannen Doherty (Beverly Hills 90210) was arrested after getting in a bar fight with another woman.
Kimchi is a traditional Korean dish made of vegetables—usually cabbage—fermented in a clay pot.
Jenny Holzer is an American conceptual artist known for projecting provocative images and phrases in public spaces.
Eleanor Roosevelt was the wife of President Franklin Roosevelt and served as First Lady from 1933-45.
A Farewell to Arms is a novel by Ernest Hemingway about an American expat in the Italian Army ambulance corps during WWI, and his love affair with an English nurse.
Kurt Cobain, guitarist and lead singer for Nirvana, struggled for years with an addiction to heroin before taking his own life in 1994.
A paraphrase of a line from the Star Trek episode “Who Mourns for Adonais?”
A line from the Tom Waits song “Pasties and a G-String.”
Could be a reference to the SnapTite line of plastic models, or the Parker Snap-tite line of valves.
The Moulin Rouge, the sleazy cabaret in this film, was the name of a French cabaret hall that opened in 1889. Toulouse-Lautrec immortalized it in his art.
The March of Dimes was founded by Franklin Roosevelt in 1938 to help fight polio (Roosevelt was himself partially paralyzed as an adult from polio).
Baywatch was a TV show about a group of young, hot lifeguards on a Southern California beach.
Van Cliburn was an American pianist who became famous in 1958 after winning the International Tchaikovsky Competition in Moscow.
Marilyn Chambers became famous in the X-rated film Behind the Green Door and went on to have a career in adult and mainstream films.
A reference to the game show Jeopardy, starring Alex Trebek.
The Big Steer Restaurant is a family diner at a truck stop in Northfield, MN.
Millie Helper was the perky neighbor on The Dick Van Dyke Show. She was played by Ann Morgan Guilbert.
Despite the Folger’s reference, this is an old ad jingle for Maxwell House coffee from the 1960s.
A reference to Khan’s famous line, which he claimed was a Klingon proverb, from Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan.
Judy is Punch’s wife in the classic puppet show Punch & Judy. She is generally beaten to death during the course of the play.
A paraphrase of a line from the Monty Python sketch “The Visitors.”
Kenny Rogers is a successful country music artist who has sold roughly 120 million records over his career.
Boog was a great first baseman for the Baltimore Orioles. He stood 6’4” and weighed 230 pounds.
A poster for the 1988 film Patty Hearst, about the heiress’s kidnapping, showed the actress’s head with the title across her mouth like a strip of tape.
A paraphrase of the classic Monty Python sketch in which a man in a pub torments a respectable chap in a bowler hat with endless strings of innuendo.
Pro Logic is a surround-sound system developed by Dolby for home theaters.
Grey Poupon is a brand of Dijon-style mustard manufactured by Kraft Foods.
Ike Turner had a popular R&B act with his wife Tina in the ‘60s & ‘70s. Years later Tina wrote about the violent abuse she endured during their marriage.
An old showbiz adage and the title of a musical comedy starring Milton Berle and Virginia Mayo.
Baileys Irish Cream is a liqueur made from cream and Irish whiskey.
“Edges light quickly” is an old ad slogan for Kingsford charcoal, which has been around since the ‘20s.
“Kodak moment” was an ad slogan used by Eastman Kodak since the ‘60s to signify an event so emotionally significant that it must be preserved on film.
This is a variant on An American in Paris, a movie musical starring Gene Kelly and Leslie Caron, that was inspired by the George Gershwin composition.
Sockarooni Sauce is one of the line of spaghetti sauces founded by actor Paul Newman; the line is called Newman’s Own.
Evita was the nickname of Eva Perón, the wife of Argentine president Juan Perón; she was wildly popular among the working classes in Argentina.
A line from the Tony Orlando and Dawn song “Knock Three Times,” which hit number one in 1971.
Barefoot in the Park is a Neil Simon play about two newlyweds who move into their first apartment. The film version starred Robert Redford and Jane Fonda.
Labor leader Jimmy Hoffa vanished in 1975, the presumed victim of a mob hit.
A reference to the “shark autopsy” scene in the movie Jaws.
An imitation of Louie the parrot from the Looney Tunes animated short Dough Ray Me-ow, said to the dimwitted choking cat Heathcliff.
Grenadine is a red, pomegranate-flavored syrup used in drinks such as the Tequila Sunrise and the Shirley Temple.
“Go in peace” is a phrase said at the end of the Catholic Mass to dismiss the congregation.
Uncle Fester is a character on the TV show The Addams Family. The role was played by Jackie Coogan. In the film version, Christopher Lloyd played Fester.
Quadrophonic sound was a 1970s version of what became home theater surround sound.
Johnny Tremain is a children’s novel about a young boy with a deformed hand caught up in the Revolutionary War.
Plath’s most famous work was the semi-autobiographical novel The Bell Jar, the story of a suicidal young woman’s mental breakdown.
An imitation of singer and cultural icon Elvis Presley. It was a phrase Elvis frequently used, usually at the end of a song while applause thundered.
The Soupy Sales Show was a daytime kids’ TV show in the ‘60s. Several recurring characters always stayed behind doors or partly offscreen.
An imitation of White Fang, a dog character on The Soupy Sales Show.
The Jordanaires were backup singers for Elvis Presley for 14 years; they sang backup for many other musicians, including Johnny Cash, Patsy Cline, and Willie Nelson.
Actor Jack Nicholson got his start in B-movies in the ‘60s, working with shlock director Roger Corman for a decade.
If we somehow missed one, let us know in the comments!
The song originated as an 1844 Thanksgiving poem by Lydia Maria Child; the family was originally headed to grandfather’s house.
In the film The Wizard of Oz, Dorothy’s companions sing wistfully about how they wish they had a brain, a heart, and a “noive,” or nerve.
A line from the song “Somewhere,” from the Leonard Bernstein musical West Side Story.
An imitation of the narrator (executive producer William Dozier) from the ‘60s TV series Batman.
“Turk’s Inn” was a kitschy steakhouse/Middle Eastern restaurant in Hayward, WI. It closed in 2015.
Godiva is a brand of high-end chocolates sold around the world. Founded in Belgium, it is now owned by a Turkish company.
An imitation of Max, the chauffeur/butler/etc. of the Harts on the ABC mystery series Hart to Hart. He was played by Lionel Stander.
A beer bong is a device designed to allow a drinker (usually a college student) to swallow a vast quantity of beer very quickly.
Super-Skrull is a supervillain in the Marvel Comics universe, usually found attempting to thwart the Fantastic Four.
Another line from “Leader of the Pack.” The song is about a girl bewailing the death of her boyfriend in a motorcycle accident.
Wart X is an OTC wart removal treatment.
KC Masterpiece BBQ sauce was invented by a Kansas City psychiatrist named Rich Davis.
Photographer Diane Arbus was known for her portraits of people on the fringes of society: nudists, transvestites, giants, etc.
The Papa Burger is a mainstay menu item at A&W restaurants, the largest of their burger “family.”
Darkman was a film about a scientist whose face is destroyed in an explosion and must don masks made of synthetic skin.
An imitation of one of Mel Blanc’s WB characters, Yosemite Sam.
A line from the classic movie The Princess Bride.
Brenda Vaccaro is a Broadway and film actress who has appeared in Midnight Cowboy and Zorro the Gay Blade.
The 1956 film Somebody Up There Likes Me was based on his autobiography.
An imitation of Bullwinkle the Moose from his classic ‘60s animated series.
Chukkas are men’s ankle-length leather boots introduced in the late ‘40s.
Silk Stalkings was a TV crime show that aired as part of “Crime Time After Prime Time” from 1990-99.
A line from the 1971 John Lennon song “Imagine,” which was his biggest solo hit.
A line from the George Gershwin song of the same name, from the movie musical An American in Paris.
Actress Rose Marie is best known for playing comedy writer Sally Rogers on The Dick Van Dyke Show.
NutraSweet is a brand of artificial sweetener used in soft drinks, gum, breath mints, and many other foods.
Morty Gunty was a well-known nightclub comedian in the ‘60s and ‘70s.
Frankenhooker is a 1990 horror flick about a medical student who, armed with his dead fiancée’s head, goes out looking for prostitutes he can harvest for spare parts.
Donny Most played Ralph Malph on the TV sitcom Happy Days.
The Long, Long Trailer is a film starring Lucille Ball and Desi Arnaz as a couple on their honeymoon in a trailer.
The “Thrilla in Manila” was the third (and last) boxing match between Muhammad Ali and Joe Frazier, held in the Philippines in 1975. Ali won after 14 horrific rounds.
Brought to you by the Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
In the early ‘90s, several house fires were caused by Pop-Tarts being left in the toaster too long. Pop-Tarts boxes actually carry flammability warnings.
Laugh-In’s “joke wall” had openings cut into it—actors could open the doors covering the holes and tell jokes through them.
The Heisman Trophy is awarded every year to the top college football player, as determined by a poll of sportswriters.
Snapple is a brand of bottled teas and juices. They were introduced in 1972 and are now available in 80 countries around the world.
The Mercury Comet was a Ford model from 1960-77, similar to the Falcon or the Maverick.
In 1956, actor Montgomery Clift crashed his car into a telephone pole after a party at Liz Taylor’s house. He had to have reconstructive surgery before resuming acting.
Minnie Mouse was Mickey’s girlfriend in the old Walt Disney shorts. She often wears a polka-dotted dress with puffed sleeves.
“Hit ‘em again, harder, harder, harder” is a football chant from the University of Wisconsin; it dates to fullback Pat Harder, who played there in 1941 & ‘42.
A line from the opening narration to the TV show Star Trek, which was voiced by series star William Shatner.
Sid Vicious was the Sex Pistols' bassist. He and girlfriend Nancy Spungen abused heroin and other drugs. She was stabbed to death and he was charged, but O.D.’d before the trial.
The custard pie in the face was Soupy’s specialty, and Fang was often the one throwing them.
Boo Radley is the recluse who obsesses the children in the Harper Lee novel To Kill a Mockingbird. He emerges at the end to save the kids from a knife-wielding man bent on revenge.
Find out the truth behind every reference in the film.
The name for the boots likely comes from the game of polo, in which a “chukka” was a period of play.
An imitation of actor Henry Fonda, who shilled for GAF products in the early ‘70s.
Señor Wences was known for his comic banter with a hand puppet named Johnny.
Iconic young film actor James Dean famously died in a car accident outside Cholame, California, in 1955.
Fang spoke in growls and grunts, which Soupy was somehow able to translate into English.
Actor and comedian Pauly Shore has starred in a number of terrible films, including Son in Law, Jury Duty, and Bio-Dome.
Johnny Hodges was a renowned alto saxophone player who played in Duke Ellington’s orchestra for 40 years.
An imitation of Desi Arnaz, who played Ricky Ricardo on I Love Lucy. Arnaz and Lucille Ball were married on the show and in real life (until they divorced in 1960).
Libbyland TV dinners were frozen dinners aimed at kids sold in the ‘70s. Their mascot was Libby the Kid (Billy the Kid spelled backwards ... sort of).
Alfred Stieglitz was a pioneer of modern art photography. Ansel Adams was famous for his photos of natural landscapes, particularly mountains.
A line from the classic British TV show Fawlty Towers, spoken by hotel owner Basil Fawlty (John Cleese).
The riff follows a drum roll, a reference to the fact that from 1950-60, the Pantages Theatre hosted the Academy Awards—including the first televised ceremony in 1953.
“Breakfast without orange juice is like a day without sunshine” was an ad tagline for Florida OJ, delivered by Miss America runner-up and anti-gay activist Anita Bryant in the ‘70s.
"Inka Dinka Doo" was comedian Jimmy Durante's signature song. He first performed it in the 1934 film Palooka.
Betty Rubble was the wife of Fred Flintstone’s pal Barney Rubble on the animated TV show The Flintstones. She had short dark hair and a darling figure.
A reference to former Washington Redskins running back John Riggins.
Love, American Style was a show that consisted of up to four short vignettes about love with various celebrity guest stars.
The family in Father Knows Best had three kids: Betty (aka “Princess”), Bud, and Kathy.
An imitation of the smarmy host who introduces Monty Python’s “Sci-Fi Sketch,” featuring man-eating, tennis-playing blancmanges from outer space.
An old Pepto-Bismol ad used this line over a rumble of thunder (to dramatize intestinal discomfort).
Ricardo Montalban did a series of ads for the Chrysler Cordoba in which he bragged about the “rich Corinthian leather” of the upholstery.
The low-calorie drink mix Crystal Light used the ad slogan “I believe in Crystal Light ‘cause I believe in me” in the ‘80s.
On the TV show Stingray, Nick Mancuso played Ray, a mysterious man who drives a Corvette Sting Ray and solves people’s problems.
The Denny’s restaurant chain began franchising that same year. Coincidence? Or conspiracy?
A reference to Episode 512, Mitchell.
The Arrangement is a film written and directed by Elia Kazan (who also wrote the novel it’s based on). It starred Kirk Douglas and Faye Dunaway.
An imitation of Darth Vader from the original Star Wars trilogy. The actor who played Luke Skywalker, Mark Hamill, starred in a flop called Corvette Summer the year after Star Wars came out.
Vince Edwards was an actor best known for playing the title role in the TV show Ben Casey.
Are you ready for the fully-annotated Brain That Wouldn't Die? Well, ready or not, here it comes!
William Proxmire was a senator from Wisconsin best known for creating the Golden Fleece Awards, which highlighted wasteful government spending.
A paraphrase of Harry Nilsson’s song “Coconut.”
Actress Nicole Eggert is best known for playing Summer Quinn on the TV series Baywatch.
A paraphrase of the song “I Can’t Say No” from the musical Oklahoma!
A paraphrase of a line from the Beatles song “Get Back.”
President Bill Clinton had a reputation for being indecisive, taking forever to appoint his cabinet and sometimes reacting slowly to crises, such as the war in Bosnia.
The Powers of Matthew Star was a 1982 TV series about a teenage boy who was actually a superpowered alien.
Snuff films are purportedly movies in which one or more persons are actually killed on film. The urban legend dates back to a 1976 film called Snuff.
Pat Summerall was a pro football player and sports broadcaster who shilled for True Value hardware stores for years, with the line “Tell ‘em Pat Summerall sent you.”
A reference to the 1968 song “Yummy, Yummy, Yummy” by the band Ohio Express.
